snippet.textDisplay:
Should easily be a Conor win there. Nate had control on the fence, but didn't do a whole lot there. Apart from like, 2 good combinations, or at least 1 good beatin'. But the punches were lazy and kinda soft, on a drained Conor. Not as impressive as the starting rounds where Nate had no answer to being dominated. Nate's biggest strength was being a lumbering zombie that never stops coming at you. But, he was eating shit the whole time he was doing it. So... I don't know if that is what should win you fights when it comes to the final decisions.

The significant hits tally was odd... they're counting some weak as shit in that tally. The quality of the hits from Conor was FAR greater. The tally of ACTUALLY significant hits, would be far higher in favour of Conor.
But anyhoo.

Take downs late into the match should could for less and less. Does Conor get any points for denying 2 take downs I wonder. Does he get more recognition later into the rounds, due to being more worn out.

It would be interesting to see matches decided later, after the footage has been looked into, and way more things are factored in. I don't delve into MMA very much, but I can see a lot of dodgy calls are likely.

snippet.textDisplay:
Round 1 - Conor (easily)
Round 2 - Conor (closer, but he did too much damage in the first 4 minutes even though he faded in the last minute)
Round 3 - Diaz (easily)
Round 4 - Conor (very close round. I think when I watched this live, I gave it to Diaz, but watching more carefully, Conor wins the boxing exchange and does good damage for 2 minutes, Diaz wins the clinch and dirty boxing for 1:20 or so, then Conor wins the boxing exchange for the last 1:40. Diaz landed more, but Conor did a lot more damage).
Round 5 - Diaz (pretty convincingly. Going purely off of damage, it's close, but the image of Conor running away and the last second takedown make this round pretty easily go to Diaz)


I think the first time I watched this live, I had it 3-2 Diaz. Rewatching, I have it 3-2 Conor. 2 or 4 could possibly go to Diaz, and it's hard to complain about it going either way.

snippet.textDisplay: I noticed Donald Cerrone's pressure has added more combinations and follow up punches right after engaging. Taking into account Conor's last training sessions and the fact that he hasn't changed too much stylistically and combination/pressure-wise (he throws 2 or 3 punches at most in each combination) leads me to believe that if Cowboy gets through the first round without being clipped by Conor's timing and speed, Cerrone will either choke him or clip him with one of those deadly and beautiful combinations. Conor's biggest weakness is still endurance, especially at 170.
